⏺ /lfg is basically a thin shell — 7 sequential slash commands with zero logic of its own. It's also missing the brainstorm step, uses
  /lavra-work (single bead) instead of /lavra-parallel, and skips /lavra-compound. It was clearly inherited from compound-engineering
  where the workflow was different.

  Against your vision it has a deeper problem: it treats the workflow as a fixed 7-step pipeline rather than something that adapts to
  the work. "Each unit of work makes the next one easier" implies the pipeline should carry context forward — locked decisions, prior
  learnings, knowledge recall — not just chain commands.

  The real question is whether /lfg should be replaced or evolved. A few ways to think about it:

  1. Drop it — /lavra-design already orchestrates the planning half. You could just make /lavra-design able to continue into execution
  (work/parallel → review → compound). That would be one coherent command embodying the full philosophy.
  2. Replace it with a proper orchestrator — /beads-go (or keep the name /lfg) that does what you described: plan with brainstorm
  context, execute with parallel, review, surface compound candidates, push. The key difference from the current /lfg is it threads
  context through each stage rather than just calling commands in a list.
  3. Keep /lfg as the "no-questions" fast path — for users who just want to throw a description at it and get code back. Minimal
  interaction. Useful for non-technical users.

  Option 2 and 3 aren't mutually exclusive — option 2 becomes /lavra-design extended into execution, option 3 becomes a one-liner entry
   point to it.

  What's your instinct — extend /lavra-design to cover the full lifecycle, or keep the planning and execution orchestrators separate
  and have /lfg (or a new name) chain them?
